  "body": "## Simple Summary\r\nAs I understand it, Vyper currently copies all calldata to memory (although it remains readonly). This is unacceptably gas-inefficient for calls with lots of data, and unnecessary.\r\n\r\n## Motivation\r\nMake it possible to write contracts in Vyper that use large amounts of calldata without running out of gas.\r\n\r\nSee also #2892 \r\n\r\n## Specification\r\nThe language syntax and semantics is unchanged. The only change is in the implementation (and gas usage, specifically for \"Initial call cost\", i.e. gas used before any function execution).\r\n\r\n## Backwards Compatibility\r\nNone for language users. I am unsure about the situation with the compiler.\r\n\r\n## Dependencies\r\nNone.\r\n\r\n## References\r\nThe #2892 VIP is an example of a pattern that would also benefit from this VIP. That one avoids unnecessary storage. Here we also avoid unnecessary memory. Both can be crucial when large data is involved.\r\n\r\n## Copyright\r\nCopyright and related rights waived via [CC0](https://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/)\r\n",
